---
import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Prose from "~/components/Prose.astro";

if (!import.meta.env.DEV) {
  return Astro.redirect("/");
}
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Chapter 1 — Editorial Type"
  description="Dev-only fixture for the editorial type system"
  lang="en"
  noindex={true}
>
  <div class="container" style="padding-block: 4rem;">
    <header style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Design Floor / Chapter 1</p>
      <h1>Editorial type system</h1>
      <p style="color: var(--color-muted); max-inline-size: 60ch;">
        Verify opsz axis, OpenType features, vertical rhythm, hierarchical
        tracking. Each block below should look intentional.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Heading levels</p>
      <div class="text-display">Display headline weight</div>
      <h1>Heading 1 — Crafting clear interfaces</h1>
      <h2>Heading 2 — A workshop on type design</h2>
      <h3>Heading 3 — Section title, mid-emphasis</h3>
      <h4>Heading 4 — Subsection lead-in</h4>
      <h5>Heading 5 — Inline group label</h5>
      <h6>Heading 6 — The smallest heading slot</h6>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Prose — default measure, no drop cap</p>
      <Prose>
        <p>
          Typography is the craft of arranging type to make written language
          legible, readable, and appealing when displayed. Good typography
          rewards attention. It carries weight without shouting, and it leaves
          space for the reader to think.
        </p>
        <p>
          A second paragraph here exercises the paragraph rhythm rule — adjacent
          paragraphs should breathe, not collide. The leading and spacing tokens
          are tuned to make stacked prose feel deliberate rather than dense.
        </p>
      </Prose>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Prose — with drop cap</p>
      <Prose dropCap>
        <p>
          When a publication wants to invite the reader in, it leans on a drop
          cap. The oversized first letter anchors the eye to the start of the
          piece and signals that this is a long-form read. We use
          <code>::first-letter</code> so the markup stays semantic and screen readers
          ignore the visual flourish.
        </p>
        <p>
          The second paragraph in a drop-cap block should resume the normal
          measure cleanly. No special handling required — only the first
          paragraph's first letter is targeted.
        </p>
      </Prose>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Oldstyle figures in flowing prose</p>
      <Prose>
        <p>
          Founded in 1985, with 247 employees and €3.2M in revenue, the firm has
          shipped over 1,420 features across 32 product lines. Notice that the
          digits drop below the baseline — these are oldstyle figures, which
          belong in body copy where they harmonize with lowercase letters.
        </p>
      </Prose>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Tabular figures — numeric table</p>
      <table
        class="tabular"
        style="border-collapse: collapse; max-inline-size: 40rem;"
      >
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th
              style="text-align: start; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-border);"
              >Quarter</th
            >
            <th
              style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-border);"
              >Revenue</th
            >
            <th
              style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-border);"
              >Customers</th
            >
            <th
              style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-block-end: 1px solid var(--color-border);"
              >Growth</th
            >
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">Q1 2025</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">€1,247,890</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">1,032</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">+12.4%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">Q2 2025</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">€1,489,210</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">1,184</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">+19.3%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">Q3 2025</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">€1,732,055</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">1,401</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">+16.3%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">Q4 2025</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">€2,108,374</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">1,673</td>
            <td style="text-align: end; padding: 0.5rem 1rem;">+21.7%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-block-end: 4rem;">
      <p class="eyebrow">Code — ligatures off</p>
      <pre
        style="background: var(--color-surface-elevated); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 1rem; overflow-x: auto;"><code>{`function compose(...fns) {
  return (x) => fns.reduceRight((acc, fn) => fn(acc), x);
}

// Ligatures like !=, ==, =>, ->, <= should NOT fuse here.
const result = compose(double, addOne)(3); // => 8`}</code></pre>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
